<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="45" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="45">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="45">
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. lamottei" order="Orthoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lamottei">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">P. lamottei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a similar 10th abdominal tergite as 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. eala" order="Orthoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eala">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">P. eala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov., but the lobes are much narrower and have a large gap between them in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. lamottei" order="Orthoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lamottei">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">P. lamottei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In addition, the male cerci are similar between the two species, stout and upcurved at their tips, however, with bifid tips in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. eala" order="Orthoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eala">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">P. eala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="45" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="45">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="45">
Typical 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brunner von Wattenwyl" authorityYear="1878" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Poreuomena" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Poreuomena" order="Orthoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">Poreuomena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species with stridulatory area marked dark brown (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 75–79" captionStartId="F15" captionText="Figures 75 - 79. Morphological details of male Poreuomena lamottei. Stridulatory area (75), stridulatory file on the underside of the left tegminal flap (76), lateral (77) and dorsal view (78) on apex of abdomen, subgenital plate (79)." figureDoi="10.3897/dez.68.60193.figures75-79" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/499194" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">75</figureCitation>
). The stridulatory file is arched and consists of about 60 teeth, of which roughly 30 large teeth are situated in the distal part and 30 smaller and evenly-spaced teeth in the proximal part (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 75–79" captionStartId="F15" captionText="Figures 75 - 79. Morphological details of male Poreuomena lamottei. Stridulatory area (75), stridulatory file on the underside of the left tegminal flap (76), lateral (77) and dorsal view (78) on apex of abdomen, subgenital plate (79)." figureDoi="10.3897/dez.68.60193.figures75-79" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/499194" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">76</figureCitation>
). The last tergite is differentiated into two stout and downcurved processes (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 75–79" captionStartId="F15" captionText="Figures 75 - 79. Morphological details of male Poreuomena lamottei. Stridulatory area (75), stridulatory file on the underside of the left tegminal flap (76), lateral (77) and dorsal view (78) on apex of abdomen, subgenital plate (79)." figureDoi="10.3897/dez.68.60193.figures75-79" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/499194" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">77</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 75–79" captionStartId="F15" captionText="Figures 75 - 79. Morphological details of male Poreuomena lamottei. Stridulatory area (75), stridulatory file on the underside of the left tegminal flap (76), lateral (77) and dorsal view (78) on apex of abdomen, subgenital plate (79)." figureDoi="10.3897/dez.68.60193.figures75-79" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/499194" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">78</figureCitation>
); the subgenital plate is elongated with two outcurved lobes (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 75–79" captionStartId="F15" captionText="Figures 75 - 79. Morphological details of male Poreuomena lamottei. Stridulatory area (75), stridulatory file on the underside of the left tegminal flap (76), lateral (77) and dorsal view (78) on apex of abdomen, subgenital plate (79)." figureDoi="10.3897/dez.68.60193.figures75-79" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/499194" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">79</figureCitation>
); the cerci are stout and incurved and possess an apical flat tip with three short processes (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 75–79" captionStartId="F15" captionText="Figures 75 - 79. Morphological details of male Poreuomena lamottei. Stridulatory area (75), stridulatory file on the underside of the left tegminal flap (76), lateral (77) and dorsal view (78) on apex of abdomen, subgenital plate (79)." figureDoi="10.3897/dez.68.60193.figures75-79" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/499194" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">78</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
